The first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering practically the same services as their Western European partners.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force traditional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have repeatedly mentioned on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (The Czech Telecommunications Office), which that the price of a SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, also confirmed it.
This is how, following the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming fees regulation, a paradoxical situation risks to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators cheaper than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds the 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there was no more space for another operator, has chorous with the operators.
It’s probably true that a classic operator with his own network seems to have no longer a lot of chance (otherwise, now he would hardly find frequencies).
But there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entrance of virtual operators to the mobile market that led to a considerable decline in prices, to which the traditional operators also had to respond.
Nevertheless, even before the entrance of trouble-festivities such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those we hear today at us were heard in the UK.
But it turned out that there was room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We don’t have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch, in Poland, of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to earn more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Add that behind the Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which possesses among others the U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to operate efficiently, they actually need much less customers than a traditional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high cost of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
This is how in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers, in the UK, SMS at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, bet on an unusual target group can also be a good advertising.
In fact, this operator is specifically targeted to men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – a operator they like and they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It’s hard to say, if such a concept would be likely to work as well in us.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone’s spokesman, doubts: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which the majority of virtual operators are based.
Especially because it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services.”
In Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic are not very promoting.
The launch of Mobilking will rather take place in other countries in our area,” said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not favorable to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do their best so that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would thus want to take a new step to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the business customer field, has not long hidden its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile.
Sooner it will be the best.
We have already negotiated this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we’ve managed to move forward in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl’s spokesman.
The future may be promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we may be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for the moment, its creation is accompanied by a total silence.
“At this point, we don’t expect there to be a place on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific compared to others.
At the moment, no subject provided for a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us," Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz said.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not recorded for the moment a viable and bilateral profitable project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: “It is practically excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should have a concrete agreement right now.”
Instead, Vodafone focuses on the fulfilment of requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the field of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what, in our opinion, means the most contribution from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in line with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore a decrease in their profits.
What does it mean to make it easier for such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to agree as larrons at the exhibition. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies.
The biggest apparent pressure on the ČTÚ, during the creation of the U:fon, was that exercised by the company T-Mobile.
This is testified by publicly accessible information drawn from the web pages of the ČTÚ.
But today, U:fon is ready to serve as an argument to not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented on this: “The competition on the mobile market has, in addition, recently been strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and above all his services, to high demands.”
But given the attitude of mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic, has no power to intervene in economic competition.
It is exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
The latter, in the face of this problem, adopted its typical position.
The entrance of a virtual operator to the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded for the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not a priori presented sufficient interest for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the UOHS Department of Foreign Relations in response to our question.
A statement thus made would not be surprised by the representatives of the operators.
But from the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and among other things also take care, that no one profits of his position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Especially as Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be found that their entry into the market has contributed to a drop in the prices of mobile telephone services."
But pressing towards a fair functioning of the market and a fall in prices is apparently not part of the interests of the UOHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which arises from their reactions.
The question, whether this is really a coincidence, is naturally posed.
Similarly, a fuel price strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to the coincidence and the hard fight of competition.
“The Office has not revealed signs of an anti-competitive behavior, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for their behavior on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably lacking even to the telecom regulator,” Chaloupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many disagreements.
Of course, there is a relevant market analysis developed by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: in order to create a virtual operator, it is necessary to obtain, at every time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
But even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the UOHS that three mobile operators are apparently acting in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face, in negotiations with all operators, similar restrictions.
Getting the responsibility back on the ČTÚ is a fairly common tour in communications, through which the ÚOHS washes the hands of the case.
We have already met this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not succeeded in making the newly adopted telecommunications law, an extension of ČTÚ’s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised a improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS need to know this very well, but their interests appear to be elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can go.
That is said, the operation of a kind of pseudo virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price list of mobile telephone services, but these are public only in part.
In most cases, it is about companies taking care of multi-level marketing.
Specific mobile services are thus offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The lists of prices of these companies usually reach only the elected.
The magic turn consists in the fact that the company makes in front of the operator figure of a classic business client, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a major customer, it gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a re-sale.
"If what you are talking about occurred, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would consider and which could lead to a cease-trafficking with the company in question," said Martina Kemrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity will not be achieved to the managers of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is opposed to such a procedure.
In fact, the activities of these companies bring them unnecessary profits, and at the same time, in contrast to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates the possible problems: “Law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a significant percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not recorded under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the way of the ordinary customers of mobile operators.”
That’s exactly what should seem strange to the CBS.
In addition, another question is raised to the UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to reveal such activity, and if it will not wish to satisfy the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibiting it.
When we’re not the most expensive
As we have mentioned several times, the entrance of virtual operators to the mobile market has brought a considerable decline in service prices.
But in almost every country where virtual operators appeared, the traditional operators were trying, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But it is precisely at this level that, in developed countries, the regulatory bodies have intervened, which did not defend the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they ended up getting the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies deal with this issue in the way a hot potato is removed by sending it to a nearby target.
Because of the experiences we have, we can’t get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable for them in these cases.
But don’t throw the hand after the cough.
If the background information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at us, the Czech mobile market may be moving back.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS will hardly remain impassible to the rejection (to discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymn has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech National Anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Day of Czech Citizenship, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national hymn Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The hymn was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, a choral interpretation and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the hymn.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously confessed to Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of the solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
“From the beginning, I tried to take care that both singers, as well as the chorus, have a good diction, so that the words are well understood, that they sing simultaneously,” he said.
The Czech National Anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj first heard in 1834 on the plaques of the Stavovské divadlo (the Theatre of the States) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), Czech original piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously suited it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couplet naturally became an integral part of the national hymn.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the Independent Czech Republic.
