Sudets call for a referendum in the United States
In 1945 the Sudanese Germans demanded that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This comes from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of Southern Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945 some group of Sudanese Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This arises, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
The Germans of Český Krumlov pray in the letter to the U.S. President not to allow "šumavská župa" (the forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
“We have well understood the situation and we want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that the U.S. troops come to the German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,” it is written in the letter, signed “People, to whom the fate of the Šumava lies in heart.”
Since the assembly in Czechoslovakia is allegedly promising – knowing the Czech national character – only of brutality, of regardless attitude, of incomprehension, of oppression and of servitude, the authors of the letter ask the U.S. President to take in his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We can't believe, that you would give this territory to a foreign state to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has not contributed in any way to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants," the letter writes.
The alleged reason why the authors can’t sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the “Czech oppressors”.
If the President of the United States doubts about the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or whether to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Sudet Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to see that the question of their expulsion from the Republic would be raised, very few of them admitted that possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Britain would get for the Sudets a certain type of autonomy.
Others thought they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of České Budějovice, engaged in the Navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp in the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
“They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would be profitable to them,” Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed, according to him, that, following the Beneš decrees, he would be expelled from the Republic.
