Olmert would return in exchange for peace almost all occupied territories
Ehud Olmert, the president of the Israeli provisional government, voted for the return of almost all the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made this statement in an interview published on Monday by the newspaper Yedioth Ahronoth.
“We have to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to return almost all territories (occupied), or even all,” Olmert said.
“We will retain a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to give the Palestinians an analogous percentage (of the Israeli territory), since without it, peace will not be made,” he added.
He admitted that the possible return would include East Jerusalem.
“He who desires security in Jerusalem, and above all does not desire that tractors and bulldozers break his feet, as it happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem,” Olmert noted referring to the two attacks in the city, in July, when several people were killed and dozens of people were injured.
According to the Prime Minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mountains, the sacred and historic places" located inside the Old Town.
“Whoever wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the whole city will be forced to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
This will not work,” he submitted later.
Retirement from the Golan Heights
Olmert also spoke in favour of Israel’s retirement from the Golan heights, which he said is an indispensable condition for the conclusion of a peace agreement with Syria.
But that would also require some efforts from Damascus.
“I do not propose to conclude peace with Syria solely on the basis of a Golan retirement,” he said.
“The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan.
