Insomnia nights for Hypo Real Estate shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted just a few weeks ago.
What a chance that the politician used the word ‘relatively’ and that he slept that the German banking sector would not be saved by the crisis movements.
This actually happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate finance Hypo Real Estate (HRE), alongside the DAX, gets a billion loan from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from turbulences in the markets.
A person confident in the situation told Reuters on Monday that the aid credits are issued up to an amount of €35 billion.
Hypo Real Estate should now pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes from both private banks and public law banks.
In the background, it is Depfa’s daughter company that suits the losses.
The state finance was, according to a newspaper article, refinanced very short-term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible since due to the unreliance to the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank’s liquidity reserve had been reduced from 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, the net capital rate also had slightly decreased from 1.6 percent to 1.45 percent.
Current and net profits from financial transactions fell to zero compared to the same period of the previous year, the profits from the allocation of determined debts and securities as well as the termination of provisions in credit transactions fell from more than 70 percent to 5 million euros.
And it is only thanks to the significant profits derived from the reimbursement of accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the reimbursement of interests according to the Book of Tax Procedures and Commercial Purchases for Konzern companies that the profit deficit of about 16 percent turned out to be moderate.
After its privatization in 1990, the former state finance had first badly speculated on industrial real estate loans, which were then affiliated with the Aareal bank.
Because the traditional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa was then more engaged in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint projects between private and state investors (Private-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the subsidiary, Hypo Real Estate must carry out amortisations that should have an essential material effect on the calculation of the group’s profits and losses that remains yet quite unclean.
The dividends were amputed.
In 2007, they were divided into two-thirds.
Hypo Real Estate has, since Depfa’s acquisition, been a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other refinancing-dependent institutions on the interbank market as it does not have any customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of credit between banks again significantly decreased, since the banks accumulated their liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs annually for a portion – approximately 50 billion euros – of the Depfa’s total credits of a short-term refinancing medium.
According to a statement by Hypo Real Estate, the need for funding of the group is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of the international financial markets largely out of operation currently.
Other sources say refinancing would be secured through the funds by the end of 2009.
Georg Funke, Chairman of HRE’s Board of Directors, explained that Hypo Real Estate Group should no longer have to use financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Institution for Financial Services Surveillance (Bafin) are based on the principle that Hypo Real Group’s market capacity is now secured.
The bank’s shareholders and creditors have to expect it.
However, having regard to the dynamic and immutability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
It is not unimaginable that the funding should not be used in its entirety.
The opposite cannot be excluded either.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest communications, still at the doors of insolvency Sunday at the end of the evening, this at least temporary rescue will not succeed in reassuring the spirits either.
The price of the stock dropped from 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
The rates of obligations, on the other hand, are good.
