The rats also have sensations.
A mouse or a coward escapes from the danger, does that mean that he also feels fear?
Neurophysician Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have sensations.
But how can we check that he feels the same when he behaves the same way as us?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without that I or anyone else has so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in that case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we penetrate into hardly practicable fields because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is faced with a danger, it does the same as many other animals: it kills, escapes or attacks.
Human beings behave the same way, so some scientists draw a comparable subjective experience from it.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make the transposition of our experience subjective to that of animals difficult.
One of the aspects is that the circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in the direction and execution functions).
This vast region is much more developed among humans than among other primates and appears to be completely absent among other beings.
At least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from the other primates.
Another significant particularity could be in the linguistic nature of man: a large part of his existence is linked to the language, which often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
But even if the consciousness should not depend on the language, it would surely influence it, so that the animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our state of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internally and subjectively, is not allowed to be measured or, due to this particular Hardware, to be analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation creates big problems to us.
Most of my developments are referring to the content of the conscious experience, but there is next to another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without taking into account their content, and that’s exactly what happened during short-term primate memory studies, especially with the example of visualization.
