“I photograph the master out of the scene to capture elements of his character” – Günther Bauer
Neither clothes nor strange clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, released from all tensions to get the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On the one hand the artist.
On the other, the person.
Unseparable except in the intimacy, in those unknown moments of the general public, where you discover in intimate gestures and stolen sights of artists who do not worry about climbing on stage.
German Günther Bauer blends in "Flamenco - people" the theatrality of a few performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of the flamenco in different angles.
Included in the programming of the Month of Flemish Photography, the exhibition “reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day,” explains the creator, who clarifies that “Flamenco – people” “can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists able to transmit on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and a character.
What interested me was creating an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of the flamenco stars.”
With the "People's Song of the Mines" festival, Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and equipment, reminds the classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day."
It is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captures the audience with his art.
The search for the essence and magic has been the constant of this work that is presented these days here in the gallery El Fotómata.
Flamenco stars like Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has turned into anthology of the flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits exhibited in the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he likes to photograph the portrait of people, know them and be able to enter into their lives for a more or less long moment.
I think in photography the portrait is the hardest genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that you sometimes don’t know or who leave you just a few minutes to be able to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I’m always trying to make my ideas reality.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at number 20 of the Mata Street (road parallel to the Hercules Peopleraie) which will be open until October 16th.
