Review: The Blood Is Back Safe
Hema-Quebec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dre Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, since Hema-Quebec has become one of the world’s safest and most effective blood suppliers.
And most importantly, it has regained the public’s confidence that had been seriously shocked by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As it is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross transfusion service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and the grounds of the public, the Government of Canada launched in February 1994 a public investigation, headed by judge Horace Krever, an investigation aimed at making light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and formulating recommendations so that such a disaster should not repeat itself.
While Judge Krever was delayed to submit his report, some provinces then set up a committee aiming to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the General Assembly has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Quebec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all the other provinces and the two territories.
“In 1998, when Hema-Quebec began its activities, only 38% of people still believed in the blood system in Quebec.
The situation was discouraging.
With efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground over the years that followed, we have recovered the public’s confidence,” she said before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, 94% of the Quebec population had now confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dre Decary, however, keeps in mind that “confidence is something extremely fragile.”
Since its establishment, on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has applied the principle of precaution.
At that time, many cases of the human form of Crazy Cow Disease, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were seen in Europe since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We then rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gellineau reports, according to which when it is unknown and that a serious disease can arise from it, in this case the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, measures of exclusion are established.
In April 1999, therefore, the blood was rejected to people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But a few years ago, it was demonstrated without any doubt that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This episode showed us that the principle of precaution that we applied was meaningful.”
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (TANs) that allow to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have shortened the silent period, which extends between the time when the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
This has significantly reduced the risk that some donors are infected without knowing it and that they cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of getting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health,” said the head of the head of Hema-Quebec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen will arise in the system.
Not later than last year appeared on the island of Reunion the Chikungunya virus which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," continues the Dre Decary before emphasizing that in addition to a safe supply, Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate supply.
“The needs are rising because the population is aging.
Since anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or plaque recharge.
The ageing population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which accounts for only 3 percent of Quebec people who are eligible for blood donation.”
Any healthy person aged 18 years and older who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is affected, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With these 3% we succeed inining an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The weaknesses are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
As today’s life is so narrow, we rarely find the time to spend an hour giving his blood,” Francis Decary regrets.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eye balls and skin which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Quebec which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The ombilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousand samples of cord blood and we are scheduled to take over a thousand each year.
We should start offering them for transplants early next year,” says the Dre Decary, which describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they can't have access to it," because Hema-Quebec has no means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
