In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Director of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Following an orwellian logic, he claims that the world’s largest gold company has initiated a six-million diffamation prosecution against three authors and a small free edition house in order to launch a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of prosecution in defamation, but the law.
Not surprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to ruin anyone who dare to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable amounts to prepare their defence and fight, with very inequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the pockets of the mining.
The tactic, in these inequal struggles, is often to ruin the defenders in order to impose a friendly settlement that will shake the opposition in addition to scary anyone who will dare to look again on the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Unlike what is done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by exchange of ideas and not by mattress.
Therefore, it was sufficient for the mining to open its books, its dossiers and to set up a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the financing of independent research teams that could have made the light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust the public and rejects from the rear hand the petitions and support letters to the authors of Black Canada.
Per Mr. Garver could explain how he can both ask for a “public” debate while neglecting the opinions of the same audience?
In the world of the vice president, it seems that this word refers only to the fat-paid lawyers and not to the whole Canadians; here’s a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even critics have the right to speech.
What doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – Barrick Gold is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does it first and foremost because he rejects the brutal way of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not within the framework of what many perceive as a prosecution-base (after the “public debate”, Barrick Gold has just filed a statement to the place of the authors of Black Canada intimating them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s persecution is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the pursuit of truth, essential to any democratic society.
