If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that dislike the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under the penalty of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
He has a right of replication.
The academic environment, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s immeasurable prosecution clearly shows that, unlike what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the academic world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it’s time for governments to put in place measures to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
