The psychology of the surcharge: why do we spend more money?
When auction sales, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in Neurology and Economics at the University of New York have managed to update the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans don’t want to be distant during this type of competition, such as an eBay auction, and that’s why they even prefer to pay a too high price.
These researches have tried to draw up a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played the lottery, while the other group participated in a lottery auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance process (IRMf), the researchers analyzed the active brain fields of the experimental subjects.
In both games, the participants could earn money, but during the auction sale of which an essential element is the surcharge of a third, the set located under the brain throne, called striatum, moved intensely during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "self-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
That’s why, according to the researchers, the rise of prices is explained by the flight to the violent striatum reaction.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
During these, three groups overleashed face to a partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they thus performed their placement.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they would win out of the game, then they would receive $15 extra, as a reward.
While the third group received him these $15 before the auctions, but the group members also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed in one on victory, while in the other on failure.
Thus proofing the hypothesis of the neurologists, the members of the team of players "contra failure" were ready for higher bets than those performed by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging helped to eliminate the contradiction between the two theories by starting, now, on a third explanation." - found Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
It is estimated to be a hundred miles of the hepatitis virus carriers in Hungary, but only seven miles follow treatment. This is due to the fact that often the patients do not know that they are the virus carriers.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
Inflammation of the liver and yellowness are characteristic, but pathogens and caused diseases differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no C vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated foods, usually accompanied by a bad general condition, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then a visible yellowness develops on the skin and on the white of the eye, the seals become clearer and the urine takes a darker color.
Worldwide, every year, one million people die from the most severe form of this pathology, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients don’t know how to get infected with the virus, because the pathogenic gene destroys the liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
The contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who suffered a blood transfusion before 1991, drug consumers and tattoos.
Currently, 200 million people in the world have chronic type C hepatitis.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor immediately after observing symptoms of unknown origin.
The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of infection disappears and the development of a cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organisms representing patients from all over the world.
Its objective is to attract attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
