The smart car imitates the flight of the bourdon
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, unless it is the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the surprising project presented at the CEATEC, which takes place in Japan, bullshit bees gave the strategic start-up idea to Nissan engineers, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini-car robot, a bio-inspired self-robot control system, type BR23C, which it has equipped with bees’ qualities, the ultimate goal is to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding any obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own, oval-shaped space, which in reality resembles a lot to our secure protective coat - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand.
Bee’s face eye plays a primary role, as it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the facet eye functions, engineers addressed the idea of the laser telometer.
This identifies obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the board microprocessor, which turns it into an immediate avoidance maneuver.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the bees’ movements, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it with a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
Unlike any system currently existing, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
"If not so, the mini-car robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must respond instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for now the collision is considered inevitable.
All this process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a glance.
Unlike the bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonal, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid the other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotative movement, acceleration and slowing as maneuver available to the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and with a larger energy concentrate, making their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is primary, not the processing of data, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism needs to process only a few input signals per second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with the intuitive logic based on the data from previous maneuver. In this way, it uses only a few dozen continuous memory-bits.
There is no need for memory of a capacity of gigabytes or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology that serves instant avoidance. According to Nissan’s estimates, this system will make its entry into serial-made cars over the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
