Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 - the Central Bureau of Statistics of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 percent compared to those of July 2008, while compared to those of a year earlier, they dropped by 3.9 percent.
As a result of the fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent compared to those of the previous month, and by 3.2 percent compared to those of the previous year.
The domestic industrial sales prices have only increased in a lesser degree: 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sector only suffered a small rise of about 0.1 percent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price rise was observed in the manufacturing industry of leather and shoe items (2,8 percent), with first, the manufacturing of bags and belt with a monthly rise of 4.6 percent, then, the production of shoes with a monthly rise of 2.5 percent.
The higher level of prices for plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the manufacturing sector of products and chemicals (1,6 percent).
A deflation resulted in the sectors of oil processing (1,4 percent), machinery and electrical equipment manufacturing (0,9 percent), as well as a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0,1 percent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase, ranging between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the energy, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent a significant weight in the national industrial operation, prices suffered an increase of 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the gas price rise established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, the oil processing sector prices have experienced the most significant rise (32.4 percent).
In the manufacturing sector of metallurgical products, prices were seen to rise by 13.2 percent, while in the major sector of food, beverage and tobacco, prices rose by 11 percent.
Price decreases have occurred in the sectors of textile and textile products (2,5 percent), as well as in the sectors of machinery and electrical equipment (0.3 percent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the price rise was between 0.6 percent and 9.1 percent.
In the whole processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
The prices of electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors have exceeded 18.7 percent that of the previous year.
Among the internal trade groups and according to the sector assignment, in August, the sectors initiating profit on investment showed the most significant monthly price rise (0.7 percent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices have risen by 0.3 percent, while those in the energy and material sectors intended for subsequent processing have not seen any changes compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for subsequent transformation (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured by 6.8 percent, while in the profit-initiating sectors, a 1.4 percent decrease.
Industrial export sales prices, in HUF, rose 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they suffered a drop of 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In a month, our national payment average weakened by 1.7 percent compared to the euro, and by 7.1 percent compared to the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 percent compared to the euro and by 15.9 percent compared to the dollar.
