Mp3 player pointed by the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to full-volume music for a prolonged period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a statement released in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the unpredictable and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
“This scientific report – let’s read in the note – shows that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable music devices, for more than an hour a day and a week, risks a permanent loss of hearing capacity.”
“I am worried that such a large number of young people who frequently use mobile music devices and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way,” says Meglena Kuneva.
“According to scientific data, this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this domain information public.
In addition, we need to review existing control systems, given the scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow the new technologies.”
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intense use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"The scientists confirm that there are good reasons to worry, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other stakeholders, what measures could eventually be taken to better protect children and adolescents from noise exposure from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European security standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but concerns are increasing regarding hearing damage that could arise from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to correctly limit these data using solutions such as reducing levels and the duration of noise exposure.
The U.S. Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decibel) for 5 hours a week, exceed the current limit for the maximum consented noise level at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This interests 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified around 2.5 and 10 million people in the U.S.
