The elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already appeared a few days ago, with the House of Representatives’ vote, contrary to the $700 billion rescue plan approved by the White House: a large number of Americans were, and is still, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the U.S. economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday who confirms it by communicating that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its former soul East Coast, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "the Washington" and the world of finance, powerful especially in the Central and South States.
The soul, just, that made itself feel despotically with the vote I spoke to you at the beginning.
However, what has just been cited is only an example of changes, of great changes that the current economic earthquake predicts or already leaves running: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and may not be only here.
In the United States and Europe, the crisis seems to have accelerated the phenomena covered for a while, so that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary resurrection, of the double category of the sovereign state, compared to a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions that, of course, have close relations with abroad, but which, above all, are involved in a large scale, the balances of people and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for the one who governs it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only national here.
Political internationalization really seems out of play or has little to say: the obvious proof is provided to us by the European Union which, shared as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, cannot decide any common political line.
And so, it is from the government of each state that everyone awaits interventions, plans of rescue and rescue, new rules, and above all a condition of credit: when one passes through a difficult period, there are only the states who possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to restore things into place.
They also have the necessary resources and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of inestimable value, elements that no market or international organization will ever be able to have in a similar way.
This new emphasis of the state-nation crisis remains in perfect harmony with the ever major importance that the latest economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite connected to this element: the territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, as we were convinced that we were now entering the kingdom of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now intended to dominate the world, we realized by a single blow, that our future will, on the contrary, have to settle its accounts more and more with the pretty little material things such as water, harvests, oil.
Things that can be transported from one place to another of the earth, but which are absolutely linked to a circular space, to a territory.
Thus, whoever is sovereign, possesses more cards than whoever is not, that is, whoever has the misfortune of living in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
Now I get to the second novelty which, however, predicts a fraction.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Policy, and thus Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the consciousness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take the situation in hand.
On the other hand, a wave of discretion for existing leaderships, economic species that have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadows.
And, in addition, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: a discretion, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of distance that tends to involve the whole class of directors in a growing number of countries in the West.
Thus increases even more the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now to their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be increasingly stranger to the opinions of the majority.
In short, The Demand for Leadership, feeds underground, a powerful and ramified movement of delegitimations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised electoral “revolutions” or, in the changes in collective mood of these recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria Bavaria, to the fall of the workers in Great Britain, to the U.S. congressist rebellion against Bush (and it could well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not happen by chance).
We have the impression that traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, some would say, have increasingly more difficulty, which does not date from today, to understand and thus to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis potentially strengthens, increases and agitates in an immeasurable manner.
In view of all this, talking about a current “mass rebellion” on the agenda seems frankly exaggerated.
But it is said well, keeping the eyes open, it is not without reason.
