Goodbye old cinema Paradiso, cities remove historic halls.
Historic cinemas are closed in favour of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinema is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the screenwriter Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the province cities.
The process of the marginalization of the cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of the large multisals, and the death of consumption of the mono rooms in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems unavoidable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, it’s often historical and memory-filled places, “it’s as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of way and so many emotions” observes the scenery of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the Jury of Cannes, and which tells the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way of living the cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional-type cinemas have closed, and the halls of the major cities have mostly paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, the Emilia Romaine is in the top with 82 lost mono movies, followed by Toscana (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the arrival of the multiplex, as it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-sales films: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romania.
"The Italian exploitation has evolved in an irrational way," observes Paolo Protti, chairman of the ANEC, "it is useful to build new structures, but it should still be guaranteed the survival of those already existing, because when a room is closed in a city, these frequencies are not necessarily all willing to go to the multiplex.
Not to mention the missing deliberation of the credit to the merchants: the state's previous debt is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Let’s note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried of these closures, decided to resolve the situation through the signature of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of this kind in Italy, to defend and promote the cinema mono halls of historic and peripheral centers.
Among the planned regulations, there are tax facility measures for managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the area with limited traffic, and will have special rates for parking spaces and in certain parking spaces.
"This is an initiative that I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope other cities will follow the example of Bologna putting in place other measures.
It is obvious, however, that in order to counter the super power of the multiplex, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, as today’s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a topic that for me, has always been important: the closure of the Bagheria Super Cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the lightning that convinced me to make "New Paradiso Cinema" which I thought about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass before the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have so much shared emotions, I turn on the other side to not see the panels dirty by dust.
